June 17, 1972. Five men are arrested in a burglary at Democratic National Committee headquarters in Washington, D.C. Two <em>Washington Post</em> reporters in their late twenties—Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein—are assigned to cover the story. Thus begins the saga in American politics that will be forever referred to as <strong>Watergate</strong>.

November 7, 1972. Richard Nixon is reelected President of the Untied States receiving all but 18 of 538 electoral votes. This will be the last time in U.S. history (through 2023) that a presidential candidate captured more than 60% of the popular vote.

August 9, 1974. Richard Nixon resigns as President of the United States.

<strong>[book:All the President's Men|1663956]</strong>, written by Woodward and Bernstein ("Woodstein"), chronicles the investigative journey that contributed to the indictment of 69 people (48 convicted) and the fall of an American president.

